 EUR/GBP spent much of late June anchored in the 0.8615\u20130.8650 area, with a prior reaction zone around 0.8618 and a closely related ceiling near 0.8610 each attracting multiple touches across that period. The sharp sell-off that began on 1 July broke cleanly through both of those levels, accelerating the decline toward the mid-0.84s by mid-month. The low printed on 15 July near 0.8454 marked the most aggressive extension of that move, and since then the pair has been recovering in a measured, unconvincing fashion. The daily candles since that low have been relatively small-bodied, with limited follow-through on any given session \u2014 a pattern consistent with a corrective bounce rather than a fresh directional impulse. The overhead structure at 0.8618 and 0.8652 now sits as a meaningful ceiling for any recovery attempt, while the 0.8454\u20130.8490 area represents the recent structural low that would need to give way to suggest a deeper deterioration.\n\nOn the H1 chart, the picture is one of tight, orderly consolidation. Price has been coiling in a narrow band roughly between 0.8527 and 0.8542 through the Asian session and into the European morning, with the most recent hourly candle nudging to a session high of 0.8537. There is no clear momentum signal in either direction on this timeframe \u2014 the range is compressed, volume is thin, and the market appears to be waiting for a catalyst. The overnight spike to 0.8542 on the 22:00 candle was promptly faded, which is worth noting as a minor rejection of the upper edge of the near-term range.\n\nToday's economic calendar is empty of scheduled risk events for both the eurozone and the UK, which goes some way toward explaining the subdued intraday conditions. With no data releases or central bank commentary pencilled in, the most likely scenario is continued range-bound behaviour unless broader risk sentiment or cross-market flows introduce an external impulse.\n\nThe read shifts meaningfully in either direction depending on how price interacts with nearby structure. A sustained move back through the 0.8618 prior reaction zone would challenge the assumption that the June-to-July decline was anything more than a temporary pause in a broader downtrend. Conversely, a failure to hold the 0.8490\u20130.8454 support band on any renewed weakness would reinforce the bearish structural argument and open the door to a more significant leg lower.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}